==Japanese==
===Noun===
[[馬]][[子]] (まご, mago)

====Sense: Packhorse driver, one who leads a packhorse====
=====Examples=====
# The popular proverb 馬子にも衣装 (まごにもいしょう, mago ni mo issho), literally "even on a packhorse driver, good clothes", meaning "good clothes can make even a packhorse driver look good"
# A [http://www2j.biglobe.ne.jp/~minwa/mago.html folktale from Okayama] called 山んばばあと馬子どん (やまんばばとまごどん, yama mbaba to mago don), roughly "The Mountain-Witch and the Packhorse Driver"
=====Sources=====
# [http://www.csse.monash.edu.au/~jwb/edict.html Jim Breen's 'EDICT'], The new Nelson Japanese-English character dictionary and NTC's New Japanese-English Dictionary list 'Packhorse driver' as (the only) English sense of 馬子.  David Galef's book on proverbs "Even Monkeys Fall From Trees" and Daniel Crump Buchanan's book "Japanese Proverbs and Sayings" both use 'packhorse driver' as the translation of 馬子.

===Personal name===

[[馬]][[子]] (うまこ, umako)
====Examples====
# 蘇我馬子 (Soga no Umako) (died 626) was a famous leader of the Soga clan. See: [[w:Soga_no_Umako|Wikipedia article on Soga no Umako]]